window.ROOT_RULES = {"system":{"name":"Root: The Roleplaying Game","publisher":"Magpie Games (2021)","engine":"Powered by the Apocalypse","roll":"2d6 + stat","tiers":{"10+":"strong hit","7-9":"weak hit","6-":"miss"},"moveRoll":{"10+":"Strong hit: you get what you want, on the best terms.","7-9":"Weak hit: you get what you want, but with a cost, complication, or lesser degree.","6-":"Miss: the GM makes a move; things go wrong (you usually still mark experience)."}},"stats":["Charm","Cunning","Finesse","Luck","Might"],"statDescriptions":{"Charm":"social grace, presence, likeability.","Cunning":"craftiness, quick thinking, deception.","Finesse":"manual dexterity, precision, stealth, marksmanship.","Luck":"fortune, providence, the favor of fate.","Might":"physical strength, toughness, force."},"statSoftRange":{"min":-1,"max":3,"hard":false},"harmTracks":[{"name":"Injury","boxes":null,"notes":"One of the three vagabond harm tracks. Marked from 0 up; when it fills you must address it. A harm track can be raised to a maximum of 6 boxes via advancement. Base starting box count is not encoded in the corpus. Represents toughness. (The Arbiter move 'Hardy' grants +1 injury box.)"},{"name":"Exhaustion","boxes":null,"notes":"One of the three vagabond harm tracks. Marked from 0 up; when it fills you must address it. Cleared by following your Nature. Max 6 boxes via advancement. Base starting box count is not encoded in the corpus. Represents reserves of energy. (The Harrier move 'Cross Country' grants +1 exhaustion box.)"},{"name":"Depletion","boxes":null,"notes":"One of the three vagabond harm tracks. Marked from 0 up; when it fills you must address it. Max 6 boxes via advancement. Base starting box count is not encoded in the corpus. Represents carried supplies / 'pockets'. (The Tinker move 'Big Pockets' grants +2 depletion boxes.)"}],"economy":{"Value":"Abstract wealth/barter (MIN 0). Playbooks set a Starting Value (see each playbook's extras.startingValue).","Load":"How much depletion-worthy gear is carried (MIN 0)."},"factions":[{"name":"The Eyrie Dynasties","description":"The old regents of the Woodland, led by one royal monarch or another alongside a court of viziers. Rigid, tradition-bound, arrogant, and ambitious.\n\nThe Eyrie Dynasties ruled the Woodland for years and years, but those times were far from peaceful. The Eyrie helped structure the Woodland into a larger entity, but they were just as likely to tear the Woodland apart as a new group of royals tried to seize power from the old group. They lost power because of just such a conflict, creating the opportunity for the Marquisate to invade. Now they’re struggling to regain the territory they see as rightfully theirs.\n\nThe Eyrie won’t be content until they have reestablished firm control over the Woodland, quelling any rebellions and pushing back any outsiders. They seek a return to the way things were."},{"name":"The Marquisate","description":"The invaders from another empire, led by the Marquise de Cat. Industrializing, forceful, opportunistic, and pragmatic.\n\nThe Marquisate is, at heart, a foreign power come from far-off Le Monde de Cat to conquer the Woodland. But it grows more tied to the Woodland each day. It builds new structures across controlled clearings; it recruits new soldiers and agents directly from ruled denizens; and it forces the culture of the Marquisate upon the Woodland, even as the Marquisate itself changes to adapt.\n\nThe core goal of the Marquisate remains what it has always been—to control the Woodland as another holding of Le Monde, a base from which the Marquise can further her ambitions. But as it adds new members to its ranks, its goals are drawn towards establishing order, industry, and prosperity in the Woodland."},{"name":"The Woodland Alliance","description":"The vehement, vocal rebels of the Woodland. Passionate, disorganized, outmatched, and zealous.\n\nThe Woodland Alliance is a new, rising power in the Woodland. There have been rebellions before, of course, but rarely have the denizens of the Woodland been able to organize revolt across multiple clearings. The Alliance’s ability to wage war across the Woodland gives them a real chance to change the nature of rulership in the Woodland.\n\nThe Woodland Alliance is determined to overcome the other factions that seek to dominate the Woodland. Ostensibly, their members also seek new government after the revolution…but their leaders only truly agree on overthrowing the old powers, not on what the new government looks like. The leaders of the Woodland Alliance also show differing levels of willingness to sacrifice the denizens themselves for the sake of the larger Woodland."},{"name":"The Denizens","description":"The average inhabitants of the Woodland. Conservative, timid, downtrodden, and standoffish.\n\nThe denizens aren’t a faction, as such—they don’t have a dominant organizing principle, besides being “civilians.” They’re the individuals throughout the Woodland who aren’t devoted to any particular faction. They’re connected by trade and by travelers’ stories.\n\nThe denizens, above all else, just want to live and be safe. There may be outliers looking to pick fights, but when denizens want to fight for causes, they veer towards membership in one of the factions. What defines the denizens is their dominant interest in continued survival amid the more powerful factions and their concern with the “ordinary” problems that arise in their day-to-day lives."},{"name":"The Vagabonds","description":"Miscreants, outcasts, and strangers. Rebels, mercenaries, and vigilantes. Vagabonds have always been a part of the Woodland. Those who weren’t safe enough, accepted enough, or satisfied enough to settle down in a clearing. Those who didn’t, couldn’t, or wouldn’t commit themselves to any particular faction. Those who were capable, skilled, and morally flexible.\n\n“Vagabond” is an all-encompassing term for this kind of denizen, an individual who moves around from clearing to clearing, taking on odd, dangerous jobs, and likely causing trouble wherever they go. A vagabond is usually highly skilled compared to the average denizen—you don’t survive for long in the lifestyle unless you’re skilled or protected by another skilled vagabond. And they usually have a certain moral flexibility, a willingness to perform jobs for different, opposing factions, or to perform jobs that other denizens might find distasteful.\n\nIn particular, there is one act that sets all vagabonds apart from the rest of the Woodland: vagabonds are willing to travel through the forests. More impressive still, vagabonds are capable of accomplishing this feat with a fair chance of surviving. Most other denizens know better; they stick to the paths or clearings, the safe spaces, the places where authorities and guards are around to deal with bandits or bears or other threats. But the vagabonds, they’ll cut through deep, thick forests, potentially traveling faster than any path-bound force. If the pay is right, they’ll gladly troop into forests to root out bandits, or find their way to ancient ruins in search of relics and treasure.\n\nThe capabilities of vagabonds are the source of their value. The Marquisate, the Eyrie Dynasties, and the Woodland Alliance all have plenty of work for vagabonds to take on. A vagabond is most likely a match for any one soldier from any faction, and many vagabonds are capable of contending with entire squads. Vagabond tinkers can create devices and equipment that no normal\n\nsmith would even conceive of; vagabond vagrants can infiltrate dangerous spaces with lies and tricks no other denizen would be brave (or mad) enough to try; vagabond rangers can move a band through forests with a speed no other force can match. Vagabonds may be dire troublemakers, but they’re so useful that most factions have a base level of tolerance for the problems they create.\n\nVagabonds don’t tend to travel in groups. They’re inherently loners, driven by their own quirks or desires to be apart from the rest of Woodland society. They’ll often meet one another through their travels, however, coming to know each other’s names and natures. They might even work together, when the job is tough and the reward is enough.\n\nIf a band of vagabonds were to arise, capable of sticking together, willing to help each other out and overcome challenges collectively…they could be a force to respect and fear. There are stories of such vagabond bands in the Woodland’s myths, though it’s hard to determine if any such tales are more than fable. But the alleged deeds of prior vagabond bands range from rescuing princes to defeating tyrants and freeing subjugated denizens.\n\nA whole band of vagabonds, shoring up each other’s weaknesses and supporting each other’s strengths, has the potential to tip the scale on the larger conflict between the factions…"}],"reputation":{"scale":[{"status":3,"label":"Legendary","effect":"a hero of the faction; positive stories, some true, are told."},{"status":2,"label":"Esteemed","effect":"an honored figure whose deeds are recognized."},{"status":1,"label":"Respected","effect":"treated with politeness and valued."},{"status":0,"label":"Unknown or Ambivalent","effect":"no clear, consistent view of you."},{"status":-1,"label":"Disdained","effect":"disliked, treated with mild contempt."},{"status":-2,"label":"Reviled","effect":"deeply scorned, two steps from a real enemy."},{"status":-3,"label":"Feared or Hated","effect":"a foe of the faction, met with deep fear and hatred."}],"statusBounds":{"min":-3,"max":3,"hard":true},"tracking":"Each Faction Reputation tracks a Status (hard -3..+3) plus checked Prestige Marked / Notoriety Marked boxes accumulating toward the next step. Filling prestige boxes to the next threshold raises status; filling notoriety boxes lowers it."},"natures":[{"name":"Arsonist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you use needlessly destructive or damaging methods to solve a problem."},{"name":"Combative","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to start a fight against overwhelming opposition."},{"name":"Competitive","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take dramatically unnecessary risks to show off."},{"name":"Cynic","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly and directly ask dangerous questions about an accepted \"truth\"."},{"name":"Defender","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you put yourself in harm's way to defend someone against injustice or dire threat."},{"name":"Dutiful","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take on a dangerous or difficult task on behalf of another."},{"name":"Extrovert","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you share a moment of real warmth, friendship, or enjoyment with someone."},{"name":"Glutton","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you overindulge on vices like drink, food, and gambling."},{"name":"Hustler","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to spring a con on a powerful or dangerous mark."},{"name":"Kleptomaniac","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to selfishly steal something valuable or important."},{"name":"Loner","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a dangerous situation alone, without backup or assistance."},{"name":"Peacemaker","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you resolve a dangerous conflict nonviolently."},{"name":"Perfectionist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you replace someone else’s existing tool or resource with something truly great."},{"name":"Pilgrim","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you find an expert in a skill you don't possess."},{"name":"Punisher","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you tell a powerful or dangerous villain to their face that you will punish them."},{"name":"Radical","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you espouse dangerous ideas to the wrong audience."},{"name":"Rebellious","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you grievously insult, defy, or anger figures of authority."},{"name":"Survivor","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to flee or cover allies' flight from a dangerous or overwhelming situation."}],"drives":[{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction.","description":"Your Reputation is the number, not simply prestige boxes. The actual value of your Reputation has to go up. You advance for any time your Reputation with any faction goes up (although again, only once per session). Whether your Reputation moves from –3 to –2 or +2 to +3, it still counts."},{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order.","description":"“Topple” means that the figure or order has been deposed, removed from power, at least temporarily (it doesn’t always have to be permanent). Who or what qualifies as a “dangerously overbearing figure or order” is a matter of discussion between players and GM, with the GM having the final call."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence.","description":"An “illicit, criminal goal” should be a goal that any force of law and order in the area would frown upon. “A believable veneer of innocence” means that, by and large, most denizens aware of the crime have no reason to blame you. Maybe they are suspicious of you, but they definitely don’t have evidence."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds.","description":"“Illicitly score a significant prize” or “pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds” offer two ways to advance with this drive. “A significant prize” can be relative to the vagabonds’ circumstances, but it should always be something either of extraordinary monetary value or of extraordinary intrinsic value—an incredibly valuable gemstone, or the gemstone that determines the next ruler of the Eyrie, respectively. “Pulling off” the caper in no way means that everything went well; all it means is that you more or less achieved your desired end. When determining whether “impressive odds” applies, think about whether or not it makes a good story; you wouldn’t recount the tale of duping some guard, but you would absolutely recount the tale of robbing the local governor’s mansion."},{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests.","description":"Both the “new wonder” and the “ruin” are understood to be “in the forests”— this drive is for vagabonds interested in exploring the forests. A new ruin is one you haven’t been to before, not necessarily one that no one has found before. A new wonder is anything impressive, surprising, exciting, or special that you find in the forests—think of it as something you could tell other denizens about and have them listen with rapt attention."},{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression.","description":"“Free a group of denizens” doesn’t mean “permanently free,” but it does mean that for the moment, their bonds are removed. “Oppression” can take many different shapes, but it must be real; the oppressed denizens must themselves believe fully in their own oppression."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure.","description":"“A serious payday or treasure” can be from anywhere, but it has to be worth a LOT of money. The amount can be relative—a “serious payday” for a dirt-poor vagabond might be less than for a rich vagabond—but should be approximately 5-Value or more."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction.","description":"Your Reputation is the number, not simply notoriety boxes. The actual value of your Reputation has to go down. You advance for any time a Reputation with any faction goes down (although again, only once per session). Whether the Reputation moves from +3 to +2 or –2 to –3, it still counts."},{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual.","description":"“Justice” is highly dependent upon the exact situation and should be discussed between the GM and the players. If need be, the GM has final say. “Wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual” means that the victim was genuinely harmed, and the perpetrator is of greater power, whether de facto or de jure."},{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself.","description":"You can name any character, including an NPC you make up from scratch or another PC if you so choose. If you name an NPC, make sure you consider how you get orders from them—if they stay put and you travel, then you can still receive orders from them through missives. “At a great cost to yourself” means that you undertake great risk or suffer great consequence in carrying out their orders. If you carry out their orders while suffering nothing, risking nothing, and paying no cost, then you haven’t satisfied the drive."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies.","description":"“Your moral principles” have to be real—no “but my moral principles say it’s fine to steal from anyone at any time!” By choosing this drive, you are saying your character has real moral principles, a code of conduct that matters to them. You don’t have to outline every aspect of their principles, but at character creation you should have a notion of some overriding principle that matters to your\n\ncharacter—“Violence is never justified,” “The poor deserve as much succor as we can give,” “Democracy is the only fair mode of government.” “Express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies” means that your principles dictated your action, and because of those actions you and your friends paid a meaningful price."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe.","description":"You can name any character, including an NPC you make up from scratch or another PC if you so choose. If you name an NPC, then you should either plan on their traveling with you, or you should understand that you are unlikely to advance with this drive unless time passes or you are specifically in their home clearing. “Protect them from significant danger” means that you either prevented them from coming to harm or rescued them from a worse fate. “When time passes and your ward is safe” means that whenever “time passes” and the Woodland’s war progresses, if your ward is more or less safe, you advance."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests.","description":"You can name any NPC, including one you make up from scratch. Do not name a PC. Whomever you choose should be a powerful foe—a real enemy who can return again and again. If you choose someone easily disposed of, then this drive will quickly become irrelevant. “Significant harm” is left up to a conversation between the GM and the players, with the GM having final say."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration.","description":"“Certain death or incarceration” here refers to the overdramatic sense of “dire straits”—obviously, if death were actually certain, then you wouldn’t have escaped! Think of it instead as making a narrow escape from what looks like impossible-to-overcome danger."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing.","description":"This is one of the most direct, simplest drives in the game—every time you arrive at another clearing, you advance. Not when you begin the journey, of course; only when you arrive."}],"basicMoves":[{"name":"Attempt a Roguish Feat","category":"Basic","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat you are skilled in, say your goal and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you achieve your goal.","7-9":"On a 7-9, mark exhaustion or one risk of your feat (GM's choice) comes to bear."},"options":[],"notes":"When you attempt a roguish feat you are NOT skilled in, you are trusting fate."},{"name":"Figure Someone Out","category":"Basic","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you try to figure someone out, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, hold 3.","7-9":"On a 7–9, hold 1."},"options":["is your character telling the truth?","what is your character really feeling?","what does your character intend to do?","what does your character wish I'd do?","how could I get your character to _______?"],"notes":"While interacting with them, spend your hold 1 for 1 to ask their player a question:"},{"name":"Persuade an NPC","category":"Basic","stat":"Charm","trigger":"When you persuade an NPC with promises or threats, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, they see things your way, provided you have given them a strong motive or reasonable bribe.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they aren't sure; the GM will tell you what you need to do to sway them."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Read a Tense Situation","category":"Basic","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you read a tense situation, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"7-9":"On a 7–9, ask 1.","10+":"On a 10+, ask 3.","any":"Take +1 when acting on the answers."},"options":["what's my best way out / in / through?","who or what is the biggest threat?","who or what is most vulnerable to me?","what should I be on the lookout for?","who is in control here?"],"notes":null},{"name":"Trick an NPC","category":"Basic","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you trick an NPC to get what you want, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they take the bait and do what you want.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they can instead choose one:"},"options":["they hesitate; you shake their confidence or weaken their morale.","they stumble; you gain a critical opportunity.","they overreact; take +1 forward against them."],"notes":null},{"name":"Trust Fate","category":"Basic","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you trust fate to get through trouble, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you scrape by or barrel through; the GM will tell you what it costs you.","10+":"On a 10+, fortune favors the bold; your panache also earns you a fleeting opportunity."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Wreck Something","category":"Basic","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you wreck something, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you seriously break it; it can't be used again until it's repaired.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you're imprecise and dangerous; you cause collateral damage, attract attention, or end up in a bad spot, GM's choice."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Help or Interfere","category":"Basic","stat":null,"trigger":"When you help or interfere with another vagabond, mark exhaustion to add +1 or –2 to their roll (after rolling).","outcomes":null,"options":["conceal your help or interference","create an opportunity or obstacle"],"notes":"Mark exhaustion again to select one of the following:"},{"name":"Plead with a PC","category":"Basic","stat":null,"trigger":"When you plead with a PC to go along with you, they clear 1-exhaustion if they agree to what you've proposed.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You may use this move only once per session."},{"name":"Engage in Melee","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you engage an enemy in melee at close or intimate range, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, trade harm.","10+":"On a 10+, pick 3.","7-9":"On a 7–9, pick 1."},"options":["inflict serious (+1) harm","suffer little (–1) harm","shift your range one step","impress, dismay, or frighten your foe"],"notes":null},{"name":"Grapple an Enemy","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you grapple with an enemy at intimate range, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you choose simultaneously. Continue making choices until someone disengages, falls unconscious, or dies.","10+":"On a 10+, you make one choice first, before beginning to make simultaneous choices."},"options":["you strike a fast blow; inflict injury","you wear them down; they mark exhaustion","you exploit weakness; mark exhaustion to inflict 2-injury","you withdraw; disengage to close range"],"notes":null},{"name":"Target Someone","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you target a vulnerable foe at far range, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you inflict injury.","10+":"On a 10+, you can strike again before they get to cover—inflict injury again—or keep your position hidden, your choice."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Cleave","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you cleave armored foes at close range, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you smash through their defenses and equipment; inflict 3-wear.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you overextend your weapon or yourself: mark wear or end up in a bad spot, your choice."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"cleave"},{"name":"Confuse Senses","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you throw something to confuse an opponent’s senses at close or intimate range, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you’ve thrown them off balance, blinded them, deafened them, or confused them, and given yourself an opportunity.","10+":"On a 10+, they have to take some time to get their bearings and restore their senses before they can act clearly again.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you have just a few moments."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"confuse senses"},{"name":"Disarm","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you target an opponent’s weapon with your strikes at close range, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they have to mark 2-exhaustion or lose their weapon—it’s well out of reach.","10+":"On a 10+, they have to mark 3-exhaustion instead of 2."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"disarm"},{"name":"Harry a Group","category":"Weapon","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you harry a group of enemies at far range, mark wear and roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, both.","7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 1:"},"options":["inflict 2-morale harm","they are pinned or blocked"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"harry a group"},{"name":"Improvise a Weapon","category":"Weapon","stat":"Cunning","trigger":"When you make a weapon out of improvised materials around you, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you make a weapon; the GM will tell you its range tag and at least one other beneficial tag based on the materials you used.","7-9":"On a 7–9, the weapon also has a weakness tag."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"improvise a weapon"},{"name":"Parry","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you try to parry the attacks of an enemy at close range, mark exhaustion and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you consume their attention.","10+":"On a 10+, all 3.","7-9":"On a 7–9, pick 1."},"options":["you inflict morale or exhaustion harm (GM’s choice)","you disarm your opponent; their weapon is out of hand, but in reach","you don’t suffer any harm"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"parry"},{"name":"Quick Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Luck","trigger":"When you fire a snap shot at an enemy at close range, roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, inflict injury.","7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 1.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2."},"options":["you don’t mark wear","you don’t mark exhaustion","you move quickly and change your position (and, if you choose, range)","you keep your target at bay—they don’t move"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"quick shot"},{"name":"Storm a Group","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you storm a group of foes in melee, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, trade harm.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 2.","7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 1."},"options":["you show them up; you inflict 2-morale harm","you keep them off-balance and confused; you inflict 2-exhaustion","you avoid their blows to the best of your ability; you suffer little (–1) harm","you use them against each other; mark exhaustion again and they inflict their harm against themselves"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"storm a group"},{"name":"Trick Shot","category":"Weapon","stat":"Finesse","trigger":"When you fire a clever shot designed to take advantage of the environment at any range, mark wear and roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"7-9":"On a 7–9, choose 2.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 3."},"options":["your shot lands in any target of your choice within range, even if it’s behind cover or hidden (inflicting injury or wear if appropriate)","your shot strikes a second available target of your choice","your shot cuts something, breaks something, or knocks something over, your choice","your shot distracts an opponent and provides an opportunity"],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"trick shot"},{"name":"Vicious Strike","category":"Weapon","stat":"Might","trigger":"When you viciously strike an opponent where they are weak at intimate or close range, mark exhaustion and roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they suffer serious (+1) harm and cannot mark wear on their armor to block it.","10+":"On a 10+, you get away with the strike.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they score a blow against you as well."},"options":[],"notes":null,"weaponTag":"vicious strike"},{"name":"Travel Through the Forest","category":"Travel","stat":null,"trigger":"When you **travel from clearing to clearing through the forest**, the band collectively decides how it travels and one member of the band rolls for the group:","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you pass through the forest to any clearing on the other side. Along the way, one of you spots an interesting site; you leave markers so you can return after you finish your trip.","10+":"On a 10+, the transit is largely safe.","7-9":"On a 7–9, something from the forest is following you; you can let it track you, or every vagabond marks exhaustion to lose it.","6-":"On a miss, you run afoul of one of the forest’s dangers during the trip, and you can’t escape it easily; deal with it before you can reach the clearing on the other side."},"options":["slowly, foraging heavily: everyone clears 2-depletion; the band collectively marks an exhaustion for each band member; –1 to the roll","carefully, avoiding trouble: the band collectively marks one depletion or exhaustion for each band member; +1 to the roll","as quickly as possible: everyone marks exhaustion and depletion; +2 to the roll"],"notes":null},{"name":"Travel Along the Path","category":"Travel","stat":null,"trigger":"When you **travel from clearing to clearing along the path**, the band collectively decides how it travels and one member of the band rolls for the group:","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you reach the next clearing in a timely fashion.","10+":"On a 10+, the trip is uninterrupted and quick.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you encounter something noteworthy on the path—a caravan, a battleground, or something else odd passing through.","6-":"On a miss, you are caught in the middle of a dangerous situation before you arrive at the next clearing."},"options":["at a relaxing pace: everyone clears 3-exhaustion; the band collectively marks a total of 2-depletion; –1 to the roll","at an average pace: everyone clears 2-exhaustion; the band collectively marks 1-depletion; +0 to the roll","safely, quickly, and under the radar: the band collectively marks 1-depletion for supplies; +1 to the roll","urgently fast: everyone marks exhaustion; +2 to the roll"],"notes":null},{"name":"End of Session (Advancement)","category":"Session","stat":null,"trigger":"When the session ends, one at a time, each player reads their drives out loud.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"The players and GM discuss whether the player fulfilled their drive during the session in an instance that wasn't already called out during the session. If they did, and they did not already advance this session for the drive in question, then they advance."},{"name":"End of Session (Update Character)","category":"Session","stat":null,"trigger":"When the session ends, one at a time, each player may choose one element of their playbook to update or change.","outcomes":null,"options":["Replace one drive with a new drive from any playbook","Replace nature with a new nature from any playbook","Replace a connection (both type and subject) with a new connection from any playbook"],"notes":"They do not have to choose anything, if they don't want to. They may choose one of the following options:"},{"name":"Ask for a Favor","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **ask for a reasonable favor based on your reputation**, roll with Reputation with the appropriate faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, they'll grant you what you want.","7-9":"On a 7–9, it costs your rep a bit; clear prestige or mark notoriety, your choice.","miss":"On a miss, they refuse and view you with suspicion; mark notoriety."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Meet Someone Important","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **meet with someone important for the first time**, roll with Reputation for their faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you're aware of their wider reputation (if any), and they're aware of yours (if any).","7-9":"On a 7-9, pick one.","10+":"On a 10+, both.","miss":"On a miss, you only know the basics about them, and they've heard stories about you and the things you've done, true or false—prepare for major complications."},"options":["you've heard stories; ask a question about them, and the GM will tell you one story you've heard about them or their interests as an answer.","they've heard something in your favor; take +1 forward when you first try to play up your connection with them and their faction."],"notes":null},{"name":"Draw Attention","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **try to publicly draw attention to yourself as an enemy of a faction**, roll with Reputation for that faction, treating it as positive (+2 or +3) for this roll.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you draw out the faction's resources to oppose you; brace yourself.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 1;","10+":"on a 10+, choose 2.","miss":"On a miss, your enemies are already moving against you quietly; the GM tells you how they catch you unprepared."},"options":["the faction employs significant military strength to chase you down","the faction deploys an available, capable NPC agent (of your choice) to chase you down","the faction is rattled by your threat; mark 2-notoriety with them"],"notes":"REQUIRES –2 OR LOWER REPUTATION"},{"name":"Sway an NPC","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **try to sway an open or vulnerable NPC by appealing to their belief in your reputation**, roll with Reputation for their faction.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you can change their mind about the world; say what you want them to believe, and the GM will rewrite their drive accordingly.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you use up some goodwill; clear 3-prestige. If you don't have enough prestige to clear, mark the remainder in notoriety.","miss":"On a miss, the NPC takes the wrong message away from what you say; the GM will rewrite their drive accordingly."},"options":[],"notes":"REQUIRES +2 OR HIGHER REPUTATION"},{"name":"Make a Pointed Threat","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **make a pointed threat to an NPC by wielding your reputation**, roll with Reputation for their faction, treating it as positive (+3) for this roll.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, they are rattled; they must surrender, retreat, or charge, GM's choice.","7-9":"On a 7–9, you must make a demonstration of your dangerous intent first, before they are rattled.","miss":"On a miss, your reputation precedes you; they reveal how they prepared for someone like you."},"options":[],"notes":"REQUIRES -3 REPUTATION"},{"name":"Command Resources","category":"Reputation","stat":"Reputation","trigger":"When you **command an NPC to give you significant, valuable resources**, roll with Reputation for their faction.","outcomes":{"10+":"On a 10+, you get what you need as soon as they can get it to you.","7-9":"On a 7–9, they impose a condition on how you can use the resources, or what you must return to the faction in recompense.","miss":"On a miss, they don't have what you need, but they tell you a way you can get it at a steep cost or some serious difficulty."},"options":[],"notes":"REQUIRES +3 REPUTATION"}],"roguishFeats":[{"name":"Acrobatics","description":"Adeptly climbing, vaulting, jumping","risks":["Break something","detection","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Blindside","description":"Backstab, murder, sneak attack, sucker punch","risks":["Draw unwanted attention","leave evidence","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Counterfeit","description":"Copying, forgery, fakery","risks":["Leave evidence","take too long","weak result"]},{"name":"Disable Device","description":"Disarming traps, turning off mechanisms","risks":["Break something","draw unwanted attention","expend resources"]},{"name":"Hide","description":"Disappear from view, remain hidden","risks":["Expend resources","leave evidence","take too long"]},{"name":"Pick Lock","description":"Open a locked door, chest, etc.","risks":["Break something","detection","plunge into danger"]},{"name":"Pickpocket","description":"Subtly steal from a pocket","risks":["Leave evidence","take too long","weak result"]},{"name":"Sleight of Hand","description":"Palming, switching, ditching, flourishes","risks":["Draw unwanted attention","leave evidence","weak result"]},{"name":"Sneak","description":"Get into or out of places without being seen","risks":["Break something","draw unwanted attention","plunge into danger"]}],"equipment":[{"name":"Dagger","value":5,"load":0,"wear":0,"range":"Intimate, close","tags":["Parry","vicious strike","+Quick: Mark exhaustion to engage in melee with Finesse instead of Might."],"description":null},{"name":"Mousefolk Short Sword","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","disarm","+Mousefolk Steel: Mark wear to engage in melee using Cunning instead of Might."],"description":null},{"name":"Foxfolk Longsword","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Disarm","vicious strike","+Foxfolk Steel: Ignore the first box of wear you mark on this item each session."],"description":null},{"name":"Rabbitfolk Axe","value":4,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Disarm","+Rabbitfolk Steel: Mark wear to engage in melee with Finesse instead of Might."],"description":null},{"name":"Greatsword","value":6,"load":2,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Cleave","storm a group","disarm","+Sharp: Mark wear when inflicting harm with this weapon to inflict 1 additional harm.","+Large: Mark exhaustion when inflicting harm with this weapon to inflict 1 additional harm.","-Bulky: This weapon cannot be hidden and is always visible while on your body. Mark exhaustion whenever you attempt a roguish feat or trust fate to sneak, hide, blindside, or perform an act of acrobatics."],"description":null},{"name":"Smithy Hammer","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Intimate, close","tags":["Cleave","+Heavy Bludgeon: Mark exhaustion to ignore your enemy's armor when you inflict harm."],"description":null},{"name":"Staff","value":4,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","+Blunted: This weapon inflicts exhaustion, not injury."],"description":null},{"name":"Spear","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Parry","+Reach: When you engage in melee, mark wear on this weapon to inflict harm instead of trading harm; you cannot use this tag if your enemy's weapon also has reach.","+Blunted: This weapon inflicts exhaustion, not injury."],"description":null},{"name":"Shortbow","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Quick shot","+Short Limbs: Mark wear to fire a quick shot at far range."],"description":null},{"name":"Longbow","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Far","tags":["Harry a group"],"description":null},{"name":"Trick Bow","value":5,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Harry","trick shot"],"description":null},{"name":"Crossbow","value":6,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":"Far","tags":["Trick shot","+Oiled String: Mark wear to use the weapon skill quick shot even if you don't have it.","+Hair Trigger: Mark wear to target a vulnerable foe at close range instead of far.","+Iron Bolts: This weapon inflicts 1 additional wear when its harm is absorbed by armor."],"description":null},{"name":"Sling","value":3,"load":0,"wear":0,"range":"Close","tags":["Harry a group"],"description":null},{"name":"Leather Armor","value":3,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Flexible: When you grapple with someone, mark exhaustion to ignore the first choice they make."],"description":null},{"name":"Chainmail","value":3,"load":2,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Tightly Woven: When you take a few seconds to repair this armor after a fight, clear 1-wear you marked during the fight.","-Weighty: This item counts as 1 additional Load."],"description":null},{"name":"Plate Armor","value":3,"load":2,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Arrow-proof: Ignore the first hit dealing injury from arrows that you suffer in a scene.","-Cumbersome: Mark 1-exhaustion when you don your armor—clear 1-exhaustion when you take it off.","-Weighty: This item counts as 1 additional Load"],"description":null},{"name":"Robes","value":2,"load":1,"wear":0,"range":null,"tags":["+Unassuming: Until you harm an enemy, they will never deem you more of a threat than other vagabonds with arms and armor."],"description":null}],"advancement":{"trigger":"Advance by following your nature or achieving a drive.","options":[{"name":"Take +1 to a stat (max +2)","description":"Add +1 to one of your stats! The highest it can go through this advancement is a +2, but there are moves you can take from several playbooks that can boost it to a +3."},{"name":"Take a new move from your playbook (max 5 moves from your own playbook)","description":"Check another box and gain another one of your own playbook’s moves! The majority of playbooks start with three moves already, so you can usually only take this advancement twice."},{"name":"Take a new move from another playbook (max 2 moves from other playbooks)","description":"You have access to the whole range of moves available in other playbooks. It’s a lot to look through, so unless you have something specific in mind you might want to take suggestions from the other players and GM, or look through the other playbooks during downtime. You can only take this advancement twice, for two total moves from other playbooks."},{"name":"Take up to two new weapon skills (max 7 total)","description":"Check off the boxes and learn two more weapon skills! Spend a bit of time thinking about from where you learned these skills—was it a teacher, or just practice, practice, practice? The maximum seven total weapon skills counts the weapon skills you start the game with, but it does NOT count any of the weapon skills you might learn as the result of a playbook move."},{"name":"Take up to two new roguish feats (max 6 total)","description":"Check off the boxes and learn two new roguish feats! Remember that means that you’ll use attempt a roguish feat and Finesse (by default) for those actions instead of trusting fate and Luck—but with the benefit that attempting a roguish feat is a lot less risky and messy than trusting fate. Like with the weapon skills, think a bit about how you learned these feats. The maximum six total roguish feats includes those you start with, but does NOT include any you might learn as the result of a playbook move."},{"name":"Add one box to any one harm track (max 6 each)","description":"Expand your harm track—give yourself greater reserves of energy (Exhaustion), bigger pockets (Depletion), or more toughness (Injury)! Each track can only increase to six boxes, though you can ultimately increase all three tracks to six boxes. This does NOT count any additional boxes you might earn as the result of a playbook move like Big Pockets (page 162)."},{"name":"Take up to two new connections (max 6 total)","description":"Take two new connections—just the mechanics, like Protector or Watcher. See page 51 for the full list of connection types. This advancement is mostly for larger vagabond bands, in which you might have a lot of companions and want a connection to each, or for when you feel very strongly that your relationship with a single vagabond has become multifaceted and thus deserving of two connections pointed at the same character."}]},"playbooks":[{"name":"The Adventurer","blurb":"You are a peaceful, diplomatic vagabond, making allies from those you aid, perhaps toppling greater powers by forging strong bonds with others.\n\nPleasant, persuasive, renowned, peaceful. The Adventurer is a speaker and negotiator, trying to resolve conflicts and better the Woodland through honest speech and genuine pleas.\n\nAs the Adventurer, you are a capable talker with a tendency towards nonviolence and resolution of conflicts through negotiation. You might be driven by a general tendency to help those in need, by the goal of rising in renown, or by a specific desire to fix the larger Woodland—but one way or another, you're interested in being viewed positively.\n\nYour fellow vagabonds will likely want to resolve things a bit more directly than you, focusing on combat, thievery, or deception to get what they desire. But in the long run, you are much more likely to achieve positive results; combat, thievery, and deception tend to have consequences, even if you get away scotfree in the moment.\n\nYour natures, \"Extrovert\" and \"Peacemaker,\" both point at your penchant for conversational interaction with other characters, your talent for relationship building. Focus on your interactions with other characters, PCs and NPCs alike.\n\nLook for chances to resolve situations by talking, without using violence, and don't shy away from risky situations. Your fellow vagabonds might have to come in to bail you out, but that's all for the best, making a more interesting game and giving everyone a chance to shine. Use your other skills and connections to support your fellow vagabonds if it does come to blows—if nothing else, assessing the situation is always pretty useful.","stats":{"Charm":2,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":0,"Might":-1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Extrovert","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you share a moment of real warmth, friendship, or enjoyment with someone."},{"name":"Peacemaker","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you resolve a dangerous conflict nonviolently."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."}],"connections":["Partner: _________ and I fought alongside each other to defend a clearing from a faction's advances...but we failed. Why did we defend the clearing? Why did we fail? Who defeated us?","Friend: I traveled with _________ for a time right after I became a vagabond. They helped keep me safe and showed me the Woodland. What keepsake did I gift them?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Sterling Reputation","trigger":"Whenever you mark any amount of prestige with a faction, mark one additional prestige.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"When you mark any amount of notoriety with a faction, you can instead clear an equivalent amount of marked prestige."},{"name":"Subduing Strikes","trigger":"When you aim to subdue an enemy quickly and nonlethally, you can engage in melee with Cunning instead of Might.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You cannot choose to inflict serious harm if you do."},{"name":"Talon on the Pulse","trigger":"When you gather information about the goings-on in a clearing, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"ask 3.","7-9":"ask 2.","6-":"your questions tip off someone dangerous."},"options":["Who holds power in this clearing?","Who is the local dissident?","What are the denizens afraid of?","What do the denizens hope for?","What opportunities exist for enterprising vagabonds?"],"notes":null},{"name":"Orator","trigger":"When you give a speech to interested denizens of a clearing, say what you are motivating them to do and roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"they will move to do it as they see fit.","10+":"choose 2.","7-9":"choose 1.","6-":"they twist your message in unpredictable ways."},"options":["They don't try to take your intent too far","They don't disband at the first sign of real resistance","They don't demand you stand at their head and lead"],"notes":null},{"name":"Well-Read","trigger":"Take +1 Cunning (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Fast Friends","trigger":"When you try to befriend an NPC you've just met by matching their personality, body language, and desires, mark exhaustion and roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"they'll look upon you favorably—ask them any one noncompromising question and they'll answer truthfully, or request a simple favor and they'll do it for you.","10+":"they really like you—they'll share a valuable secret or grant you a serious favor instead.","6-":"you read them totally wrong, and their displeasure costs you."},"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Disarm","Harry","Improvise","Parry"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Sleight of Hand"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 9"],"extras":{"startingValue":9}},{"name":"The Arbiter","blurb":"You are a powerful, obstinate vagabond, serving as somewhere between a mercenary and a protector, perhaps taking sides too easily in the greater conflict between the factions.\n\nJust, mighty, committed, defensive. The Arbiter is a capable warrior and protector, intervening in conflicts on one side or another, defending the innocent and punishing the transgressors.\n\nAs the Arbiter, you are one of the most competent fighters among your vagabond brethren, with a tendency to act like a wandering knight—a force of martial prowess without a single specific cause, but with a sense of justice all your own.\n\nOther powers and figures are likely to want you on their side. After all, you are one of the best warriors they could have fighting for them! A key question for the Arbiter is always \"On whose side do you fight?\" Maybe you defend the innocent from tyrants, but maybe you pick the side you think is most likely to bring about peace.\n\nYour natures, \"Defender\" and \"Punisher,\" speak to the two sides of the Arbiter—one as a protector keeping harm from your wards, and the other as an avenger pursuing justice against wrongdoers. Both of them are likely to aim you at dangerous and powerful foes, so be on the lookout for antagonists who are targeting other denizens (so you can protect them) or who are deserving of justice.\n\nTry to find causes to fight for or against. You're skilled at fighting, but if you only wait for fights to come to you, you might find yourself waiting more than you'd like. And don't hesitate to use other skills like Carry a Big Stick to try to avoid fights—you're skilled at fighting, but martial conflict almost always creates new problems.","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":0,"Luck":-1,"Might":2},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Defender","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you put yourself in harm's way to defend someone against injustice or dire threat."},{"name":"Punisher","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you tell a powerful or dangerous villain to their face that you will punish them."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Justice","condition":"Advance when you achieve justice for someone wronged by a powerful, wealthy, or high-status individual."},{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Loyalty","condition":"You’re loyal to someone; name them. Advance when you obey their order at a great cost to yourself."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."}],"connections":["Protector: I once protected _________ from a mortal blow during a fight, and I would do it again. Why?","Partner: _________ and I together helped a faction take control of a clearing, and share responsibility for it."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Brute","trigger":"","outcomes":{"any":"Take +1 Might (max +3)."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Carry a Big Stick","trigger":"When you use words to pause an argument or violent conflict between others, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"they choose: mark 2-exhaustion and keep going, or stop for now.","10+":"take +1 ongoing to dealing with them peacefully.","miss":"NPCs turn their anger to you, and PCs take +1 ongoing against you for the scene."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Crash and Smash","trigger":"When you smash your way through scenery to reach someone or something, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"you reach your target.","10+":"choose 1.","7-9":"choose 2.","miss":"you smash through, but you leave yourself totally vulnerable on the other side."},"options":["You hurt yourself: mark 1 injury","You break an important part of your surroundings","You damage or leave behind a piece of gear (GM's choice)"],"notes":null},{"name":"Hardy","trigger":"","outcomes":{"any":"Take 1 additional injury box. Whenever time passes or you journey to a new clearing, you can clear 2 injury boxes automatically."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Strong Draw","trigger":"When you target someone with a bow, mark wear on the bow to roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"mark exhaustion to inflict 1 additional injury. Mark exhaustion again to make your shot ignore the enemy's armor—they cannot mark wear to absorb the injury."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Guardian","trigger":"When you defend someone or something from an immediate NPC or environmental threat, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"you keep them safe and choose one.","7-9":"it costs: expose yourself to danger or escalate the situation.","miss":"you take the full brunt of the blow intended for your protectee, and the threat has you where it wants you."},"options":["Draw the attention of the threat; they focus on you now","Put the threat in a vulnerable spot; take +1 forward to counterstrike","Push the threat back; you and your protectee have a chance to maneuver or flee"],"notes":null}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Cleave","Disarm","Parry","Storm a Group"],"startingRoguishFeats":[],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 10"],"extras":{"startingValue":10}},{"name":"The Harrier","blurb":"You are a quick, enterprising vagabond, racing easily from building to building and clearing to clearing without anything stopping you, perhaps finding yourself in places others would rather keep secret or hidden.\n\nMobile, crafty, unbound, criminal. The Harrier is a moving, traveling vagabond, often specializing as a freelancer for other powers. When they need something smuggled in or out of a clearing, they'll turn to the Harrier.\n\nAs the Harrier, you have a lot of useful skills, and you should seek opportunities to apply them. You're not as obvious a mercenary as a warrior like the Arbiter, but plenty of black marketeers would love to have a Harrier on their payroll.\n\nThe Harrier is very effective at getting jobs and other tasks from NPCs, but is just as effective at finding their own opportunities to take advantage of alongside their fellow vagabonds. As the Harrier, don't be afraid of trying to betray greater powers for some gain or profit—it will often fit your drives perfectly.\n\nYour natures, \"Dutiful\" and \"Competitive,\" both incentivize taking action—doing over planning or thinking. Dutiful incentivizes taking on jobs on behalf of others, so don't hesitate to figure out what NPCs want and ask them for work. Competitive incentivizes taking on risks—it's easy enough to hit Competitive in the middle of any job. Both of them shine a light on the Harrier's emphasis on constantly moving.\n\nFor the Harrier, your drives are even more crucial—if you're ever looking for the next big thing to do, look at your drives and focus on that. But you can easily get by supporting other vagabonds in their goals, especially because it's often easy to hitch your drives and your nature to their objectives.","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":2,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Dutiful","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take on a dangerous or difficult task on behalf of another."},{"name":"Competitive","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you take dramatically unnecessary risks to show off."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"connections":["Professional: ___________ and I tried to blaze a new trail between two clearings; without the support of the major factions, it never fully came to fruition.","Friend: ___________ and I forged a bond while investigating a ruin deep in the woods. What strange minor trinkets do each of you carry from that expedition?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Cross Country","trigger":"Take one extra box of exhaustion. When your exhaustion track is full and you must mark exhaustion, you may choose to mark an equivalent amount of injury instead of being removed from the situation or going unconscious.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Fleet of Foot and Hand","trigger":"Take +1 Finesse (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Don't Shoot the Messenger","trigger":"Take the Counterfeit roguish feat (it does not count against your limit.) When you pretend to be an innocuous messenger carrying a missive of import to trick someone, roll with Luck instead of Cunning.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Parkour","trigger":"When you dash your way through a chaotic scene or fight, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3.","7-9":"hold 2. Spend your hold 1-for-1 to dash to something within sight and reach without being stopped, or to dash away from something nearby without being stopped. You can dash away from an enemy even at the moment they attack.","miss":"your surroundings trip you up, and you're caught in place while danger closes in."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Traveler Extraordinaire","trigger":"When you travel along the paths to another clearing, you can always give +1 to the roll or clear 2-exhaustion, your choice. When you travel through the forest to another clearing, you can always give +1 to the roll or clear 2-depletion, your choice. In both cases, before you arrive at the next clearing, you can ask the GM any two questions about the next clearing, based on what you remember from your last time through.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Smuggler's Path","trigger":"You've got a good sense for finding secret paths and doors. When you spend time looking for a secret way in or out of a place that might have one, mark exhaustion and roll with Luck.","outcomes":{"hit":"you find a hidden path—the GM will detail it and to where it leads.","10+":"there's something along or inside the path of value to you—the GM will tell you what.","miss":"you find a secret path...and someone else is using it right this second. They probably won't be happy you found their secret."},"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Disarm","Harry","Quick Shot","Trick Shot"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Sneak"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 9"],"extras":{"startingValue":9}},{"name":"The Ranger","blurb":"You are a capable, stealthy vagabond, centered on the forests that fill the Woodland between the clearings, more interested in the wilds than in the company of other Woodland denizens or their society.\n\nSolitary, dangerous, stealthy, wild. The Ranger is an experienced forestdwelling vagabond, capable of fighting and surviving in the Woodland's most dangerous spaces.\n\nAs the Ranger, you are a skilled and dangerous fighter, but your emphasis is on stealth—striking from shadows, escaping from dangerous conflicts, and more. You can handle yourself in a straight-up fight, but it's likely not your preferred form of conflict.\n\nAt heart, the Ranger is a bit more of a loner than the rest of the vagabonds, but they have found the advantages of the band drawing them in. Companionship, teamwork, shared burdens—these things will always draw the Ranger back to the band. You can play them as gruff and standoffish as you want, but remember that the Ranger belongs with the band as long as they are a PC.\n\nYour natures, \"Loner\" and \"Cynic,\" point to your antisocial behaviors. Loner is obviously pointed at your tendency to try to solve problems alone—keep in mind that it's going to cause you trouble, and that it's about individual situations, not leaving your band behind and journeying to another clearing altogether. Cynic draws attention to your desire to speak truth to power, to question assumptions of the factions and powers that be…but in ways very likely to draw the ire of those very same powers.\n\nLean into your connections and your fellow vagabonds. Your drives and your nature might draw you into conflicts that seem isolated, but they're always more fun when the other PCs can get involved eventually, even if they mostly end up rescuing you!","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Loner","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you enter a dangerous situation alone, without backup or assistance."},{"name":"Cynic","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you openly and directly ask dangerous questions about an accepted \"truth\"."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Discovery","condition":"Advance when you encounter a new wonder or ruin in the forests."},{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."}],"connections":["Watcher: I was tricked, conned, or deceived by ___________ once. Why do I choose to continue working with them?","Protector: I did something that would have gotten me the enmity of a Woodland faction—if ___________ hadn't covered for me. What did I do? Why and how did they protect me? Regardless, I feel indebted to them."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Silent Paws","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat to sneak or hide, you can mark 2-exhaustion to shift a miss to a 7-9.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You are adept at slipping into and out of dangerous situations without anyone noticing."},{"name":"Slip Away","trigger":"When you take advantage of an opening to escape from a dangerous situation, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you get away.","10+":"On a 10+, choose 1.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose 2:","6-":"On a miss, you escape, but it costs you—mark injury or exhaustion, GM's choice—and you leave ample evidence behind for your foes to track and follow you."},"options":["You suffer injury or exhaustion (GM's choice) during your escape","You end up in another dangerous situation","You leave something important behind"],"notes":null},{"name":"Poisons and Antidotes","trigger":"When you brew a poison, mark depletion and say what effect you want it to have: sleep, weakness, inebriation, or death.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You have expertise in the poisons and antidotes of the Woodland. Any poison you make requires ingestion or injection; you can use the poison on your weapon or put it in your target's food or drink. When you study a poison or its effects to make an antidote, the GM will tell you what special ingredient you'll need. Get the ingredient and mark depletion to brew the antidote."},{"name":"Forager","trigger":"When you travel or pass into a forest, before making any travel move, you can clear your choice of:","outcomes":null,"options":["Up to 3-depletion","Up to 2-exhaustion","Up to 2-injury"],"notes":null},{"name":"Threatening Visage","trigger":"When you persuade an NPC with open threats or naked steel, roll with Might instead of Charm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Dirty Fighter","trigger":"Take two of the following weapon skills: Trick Shot, Confuse Senses, Improvise Weapon, Disarm, Vicious Strike.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"None of the skills you take with this move count against your limit."}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Cleave","Disarm","Harry","Vicious Strike"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Hide","Sneak"],"startingEquipment":[],"extras":{"startingValue":null,"note":"No Starting Value / Starting Equipment entry given in the corpus for The Ranger."}},{"name":"The Ronin","blurb":"You are a skilled, willful vagabond, formerly a servant of a lord in a different land, now masterless. You came to the Woodland to live as a free vagabond.\n\nWell-trained, willful, expatriate, free. The Ronin is a former servant and warrior of some master in a land far from here, now broken from their lord and come to this land as a free agent.\n\nAs the Ronin, you are quite a capable fighter, but you're also a social character—a \"servant\" well used to figuring out the vagaries of the court, the needs of a lord, and the ways of propriety. You're at home both on the battlefield and in the halls of power.\n\nThe Ronin, by definition, is originally from somewhere other than the Woodland. They left that life behind with the demise of their master—one of the background questions on the playbook is all about what happened to that master. As such, the Ronin has a different cultural background with different traditions and ideas than a Woodland denizen.\n\nThat said, the Ronin is still a denizen like the other characters. They have the same overarching drives and desires. And the Ronin certainly has been in the Woodland long enough to be able to easily function there, though NPCs recognizing the Ronin's background and treating them differently can make for dramatic trouble (if everyone at the table is on board with those issues coming to the fore).\n\nIn playing a Ronin, be sure to avoid some of the pitfalls of playing a character of a different culture—no accents, no silly misunderstandings about commonplace objects, no broken grammatical constructions. The Ronin is competent and capable, and they've learned how to navigate the Woodland.","stats":{"Charm":0,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":-1,"Might":2},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Survivor","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to flee or cover allies' flight from a dangerous or overwhelming situation."},{"name":"Pilgrim","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you find an expert in a skill you don't possess."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Principles","condition":"Advance when you express or embody your moral principles at great cost to yourself or your allies."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"connections":["Partner: __________ and I worked together on my first real task of significance in the Woodland, deposing a dangerous authority figure of a faction. Who did we depose? Why?","Watcher: I see in ____________ many reminders of my old master. I am drawn to them, even as I watch them carefully. What is it that reminds me of my old master? How do they feel about my watchful eyes?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Always Armed","trigger":"When you deal harm with an improvised weapon, deal +1 harm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"Take the weapon skill Improvise a Weapon (it does not count against your limit). When you deal harm with an improvised weapon, deal +1 harm."},{"name":"Knowing a Lord's Will","trigger":"When you figure out a denizen of status, authority, or power, roll with Might instead of Charm.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"When you trick a denizen of status, authority, or power by playing subordinate, roll with Might instead of Cunning."},{"name":"Well-Mannered","trigger":"When you enter a social environment dependent on manners and etiquette, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3","7-9":"hold 2","miss":"the rules of etiquette here are far different from what you expected; mark exhaustion as you commit a gravely impolite error."},"options":["Cover up a social faux pas on behalf of yourself or an ally; clear 1-exhaustion","Call out someone else's social faux pas; inflict 1-morale harm on them","Charm someone; take +1 ongoing to speak to them while you have hold","Demonstrate your value; mark prestige with a powerful denizen's faction"],"notes":"Lose all hold when you leave or when social rules fall apart. Spend hold 1-for-1 to:"},{"name":"Fealty","trigger":"When you commit yourself to the cause of someone you deem worthy, swear an oath to them stating what task you will complete on their behalf.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"Mark exhaustion to reroll a move made in pursuit of that task. You cannot commit yourself to another cause until you accomplish the first, or break your oath. If you break your oath, fill your exhaustion track and mark 4-notoriety with the faction whose trust you betrayed. If you fulfill your oath, mark 4-prestige with the faction whose trust you kept."},{"name":"The Rules of War","trigger":"When you call upon a reasonable foe to uphold a rule of war, roll with Might.","outcomes":{"hit":"they feel obliged; choose one below they must follow.","7-9":"they choose one that you must follow; disobey, and the obligation ends.","miss":"they feel no obligation to your ideas of war; prepare for a brutal lesson in the rules they adhere to."},"options":["Show mercy to surrendering foes and prisoners","Refrain from underhanded tactics in a fight","Face each other without aid, back-up, or assistance","Keep the violence away from the unarmed or innocent","Fight to surrender or subdual, without retreat"],"notes":null},{"name":"Always Watching","trigger":"Take +1 Cunning (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Cleave","Harry","Storm a Group","Vicious Strike"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Blindside"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 11"],"extras":{"startingValue":11,"background":"One of the background questions on the playbook concerns what happened to the Ronin's former master (their demise, which freed the Ronin)."}},{"name":"The Scoundrel","blurb":"You are a lucky, dangerous vagabond, acting more as destroyer and troublemaker than anything else, perhaps creating chaos and destruction for its own sake.\n\nDestructive, risky, wild, mischievous. The Scoundrel is a stealthy destroyer, an arsonist, rebel, and agent of chaos in a mask.\n\nAs the Scoundrel, you're a troublemaker, for good and for ill. You can cause a lot of trouble for tyrants and oppressors, but you'll create just as much trouble for your comrades. That's okay, though—your high Luck means you're just about as good as can be expected at getting out of those sticky situations you create.\n\nThe Scoundrel might have a bit of a tendency to be antisocial with the rest of the vagabonds—if they grow too frustrated with the way you blow up situations and use dangerous and extreme solutions, then the other vagabonds might want to part ways with the troublemaker. You should make liberal use of the pleading to get the other PCs to go along with your plans, and you should play hard into your connections—you've got a friend and a partner at least, and those positive relationships should help make up for your mischief!\n\nThat said, when playing a Scoundrel, be sure that you don't create meaningless chaos (at least, not often). Even if you have the Chaos drive, you're actually after a particular goal, not just chaos for its own sake. Play towards your goals, towards accomplishing ends—even if you tend to blow things up along the way, it's more fun if the explosions are purposeful.\n\nYour natures both point at your troublemaking essence. If you're an \"Arsonist,\" then you have incentive to cause more destruction than necessary in accomplishing your ends. If you're \"Combative,\" then you have incentive to start fights you probably can't win. In both cases, you're going to cause a LOT of trouble to get back your exhaustion. The more you can get buy-in from your fellow vagabonds before things explode, the better.\n\nBut when the time comes, don't hesitate to hit your moves and blow stuff up. The Scoundrel is a fun playbook because of the trouble it creates—it's not a playbook for playing it safe, no matter what your pals think!","stats":{"Charm":1,"Cunning":-1,"Finesse":0,"Luck":2,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Arsonist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you use needlessly destructive or damaging methods to solve a problem."},{"name":"Combative","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to start a fight against overwhelming opposition."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Crime","condition":"Advance when you illicitly score a significant prize or pull off an illegal caper against impressive odds."},{"name":"Infamy","condition":"Advance when you decrease your Reputation with any faction."}],"connections":["Friend: ____________ and I once met and pulled off a mad, impossible stunt together. What did we do? Why?","Partner: ____________ and I destroyed a faction's resource, on behalf of an opposing faction. Why?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Explosive Personality","trigger":"When you wreck something with flagrantly dangerous means (explosives, uncontrolled flame, etc.), roll with Luck instead of Might.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Create to Destroy","trigger":"When you use available materials to rig up a dangerous device, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you cobble together something that will do what you want, one time.","10+":"On a 10+, choose one.","7-9":"On a 7-9, choose two. The device is:","miss":"On a miss, you need some vital component to finish it; the GM will tell you what."},"options":["More dangerous than intended","Larger or more unwieldy than intended","More temperamental and fragile than intended"],"notes":null},{"name":"It's a Distraction!","trigger":"When you attempt a roguish feat to blindside someone while they are distracted by environmental dangers (a raging fire, an oncoming flood, etc.), roll with Luck instead of Cunning.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You gain the roguish feat Blindside (it does not count against your limit)."},{"name":"Daredevil","trigger":"When you dive into a dangerous situation without forethought or planning, treat yourself as having \"Luck Armor,\" with 1 box of wear (remember, armor is only \"destroyed\" when you would mark another box of wear, and all its boxes are full).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You're at your luckiest when you go into danger without hesitation. The \"Luck Armor\" automatically goes away once the danger has passed, and the next time you would have \"Luck Armor,\" you gain it as if it was brand new with clear boxes."},{"name":"Danger Mask","trigger":"While you have your mask on, any notoriety you gain is doubled, any prestige you gain is halved, and take +1 to trust fate and all Scoundrel playbook moves.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"You have a mask or outfit you wear when you go about your most destructive work—more of a calling card, an identifier of \"the real you,\" than a disguise. Treat it as a piece of equipment with two boxes of wear. If your mask is ever taken from you, mark exhaustion. If your mask is ever destroyed, mark 4-exhaustion. If your mask is destroyed, you can make a new mask when time passes."},{"name":"Better Lucky than Good","trigger":"When you use a weapon move (basic or skilled), mark exhaustion to roll with Luck instead of the listed stat.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Confuse Senses","Improvise","Quick Shot","Vicious Strike"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Acrobatics","Sneak","Hide"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 8"],"extras":{"startingValue":8}},{"name":"The Thief","blurb":"You are a cunning, criminal vagabond, capable of stealing even the most well-guarded treasures, perhaps committed to crime and theft for its own sake.\n\nCrafty, professional, nimble, quiet. The Thief is the ultimate criminal, taking whatever valuables they can grab from any treasure room, vault, or safe, no matter how secure.\n\nAs the Thief, you are likely the single best vagabond in your band with regard to roguish feats. Your high Finesse and your four chosen roguish feats make you more than capable of shoring up any gaps in your band's skill set or solving problems through illicit action. You should be looking for ways to bring your skills to bear and solve problems.\n\nYou're not in trouble when it comes to fights—you are a vagabond, after all—but by default, you'd likely prefer to solve things through stealth and guile. That said, part of the push-pull in the playbook is that your fellow vagabonds aren't going to be able to follow you into every place you sneak. The more you can create opportunities for your fellows to follow by opening doors, leaving ropes out open windows, and so on, the more you can rely on them when a fight (inevitably) breaks out.\n\nYour general skill set is about getting through trouble stealthily, without calling attentions to your activities, so your natures instead push you to cause some problems for yourself. That's great! Embrace the trouble you get into by selfishly stealing things and grievously insulting authority figures.\n\nYour natures—\"Kleptomaniac\" and \"Rebellious\"—are both likely to get you into hot water. \"Selfishly steal something\" always means that you're stealing something you want, and something likely to cause you and yours trouble, instead of stealing something that you and your whole band have agreed is necessary. Similarly, \"grievously insult, defy, or anger\" means that whatever you do, you're pretty much guaranteed the authority figure will react—if you haven't taken enough action that they react, then you haven't hit the trigger.\n\nAt its heart, the Thief is a pretty direct, simple playbook—steal stuff and get away with it!—but you provide real utility to the rest of your band. So pay attention to their goals and desires, too. Much of the time, they'd love to have your help picking locks, sneaking into places, and nabbing vital treasures. You get to show off and help a friend!","stats":{"Charm":0,"Cunning":0,"Finesse":2,"Luck":1,"Might":-1},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Kleptomaniac","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to selfishly steal something valuable or important."},{"name":"Rebellious","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you grievously insult, defy, or anger figures of authority."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Freedom","condition":"Advance when you free a group of denizens from oppression."},{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."}],"connections":["Professional: I stole something important, something needed or craved, for ___________. I proved my worth to them.","Friend: ____________ sprang to get me out of holding, whether they bailed me out or rescued me. I owe them."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Breaking and Entering","trigger":"When you attempt roguish feats to get into or out of a place you've previously been, you can mark exhaustion to make the move as if you had rolled a 10+, instead of rolling.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Disappear Into the Dark","trigger":"When you slip into shadows while unnoticed, mark exhaustion and hold 1.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"As long as you remain quiet, move slowly, and hold 1 for this move, you will remain hidden. If you inadvertently reveal yourself, lose your hold. Spend your hold to reveal yourself from a darkened place, suddenly and without warning. If you attack someone immediately after spending the hold, take +3 on the roll."},{"name":"Rope-a-Dope","trigger":"When you evade and dodge your enemy so as to tire them out, roll with Finesse.","outcomes":{"hit":"On a hit, you can mark exhaustion to make them mark 2-exhaustion.","10+":"On a 10+, you can mark exhaustion to make them mark 3-exhaustion.","miss":"On a miss, they catch you in the middle of a dodge—you're at their mercy."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Small Hands","trigger":"When you grapple with an enemy larger than you, roll with Finesse instead of Might.","outcomes":{"miss":"On a miss, they overpower you—you're at their mercy."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Master Thief","trigger":"Take +1 Finesse (max +3).","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Nose for Gold","trigger":"When you figure someone out, you can always ask (even on a miss):","outcomes":null,"options":["what is the most valuable thing they are carrying?"],"notes":"When you read a tense situation, you can always ask (even on a miss):\n· what is the most valuable thing here?"}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Confuse Senses","Improvise","Parry","Trick Shot"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Choose any four roguish feats to start (page 69)"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 6"],"extras":{"startingValue":6,"roguishFeatChoice":"The Thief chooses any four roguish feats to start (page 69)."}},{"name":"The Tinker","blurb":"You are an adept, clever vagabond, interested in mechanisms and craftsmanship, perhaps possessed of ideas that separate you from those around you.\n\nGenius, awkward, incautious, inventive. The Tinker is an incredibly capable maker and mechanic, solving problems through devices and clever…well…tinkering.\n\nThe Tinker is more than a crafter or a smith—they’re a true wonder with mechanics, and they’re able to string up all manner of equipment and devices with base supplies. Compared to most clearings’ smiths and crafters, the Tinker is practically a wizard.\n\nBetween the Tinker’s Toolbox and Repair moves, they are oriented more towards longer-term goals and objectives than nearly any other playbook. In practice, that means the Tinker’s projects will often be the spur for the PCs to take action; the Tinker needs the other vagabonds’ help to get the materials they need, or to secure a meeting with the Royal Engineer of the Marquisate, or whatever the case may be.\n\nThe Tinker’s natures point at their potentially strange, “exile-worthy” beliefs in ways that prompt them to action. A “Perfectionist” Tinker can get in trouble when they help the wrong denizens. And a “Radical” Tinker might try to improve minds as well as materials and wind up saying the wrong thing to the wrong crowd, for example suggesting that monarchy might not be the greatest governmental system to a room full of Eyrie nobles.\n\nThe Tinker absolutely needs the other vagabonds in the band to support them. The Tinker is far from incompetent (like all vagabonds), but unlike some other vagabonds the Tinker is no match for a troop of armed soldiers on their own. Fortunately, every other vagabond will love having a Tinker around to repair their equipment and sometimes even arm them anew.","stats":{"Charm":-1,"Cunning":2,"Finesse":1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Perfectionist","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you replace someone else’s existing tool or resource with something truly great."},{"name":"Radical","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you espouse dangerous ideas to the wrong audience."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Greed","condition":"Advance when you secure a serious payday or treasure."},{"name":"Ambition","condition":"Advance when you increase your Reputation with any faction."},{"name":"Revenge","condition":"Name your foe. Advance when you cause significant harm to them or their interests."},{"name":"Protection","condition":"Name your ward. Advance when you protect them from significant danger, or when time passes and your ward is safe."}],"connections":["Professional: ____________ and I have been working together well for a while. We read each other’s moves easily.","Family: _____________ and I had each other’s back when we were run out of a clearing because our natures got out of hand."],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Toolbox","trigger":"When you open up your toolkit and dedicate yourself to making a thing or to getting to the bottom of something, decide what and tell the GM.","outcomes":{"any":"The GM will give you between 1 to 4 conditions you must fulfill to accomplish your goal, including time taken, materials needed, help needed, facilities/tools needed, or the limits on the project. When you accomplish the conditions, you accomplish the goal."},"options":["Feature: assorted scrap wood","Feature: assorted gears and springs","Feature: esoteric hand tools","Feature: manuals","Feature: assorted medicines","Feature: portable alchemy kit","Feature: sewing kit","Feature: cookware","Feature: minor explosives","Drawback: heavy (counts as 2 Load instead of 1)","Drawback: bulky & obvious","Drawback: stolen","Drawback: fragile"],"notes":"You have a kit of tools and supplies with which you work on long-term projects. Choose two features and one drawback from the options."},{"name":"Repair","trigger":"When you repair destroyed personal equipment with your toolbox, the GM will set one condition as per the Toolbox move.","outcomes":{"any":"Fulfill it, and clear all wear for that equipment. When you repair damaged personal equipment with your toolkit, you do it as long as you spend depletion or Value, 1 for 1, for each box of wear you clear."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Big Pockets","trigger":"Take two extra boxes of depletion.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Jury Rig","trigger":"When you create a makeshift device on the fly, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"you create a device that works once, then breaks.","10+":"choose one: It works exceptionally well; You get an additional use out of it","miss":"the device works, but it has an unintended side effect that the GM will reveal when you use it."},"options":["It works exceptionally well","You get an additional use out of it"],"notes":null},{"name":"Nimble Mind","trigger":"When you attempt roguish feats involving mechanisms or locks, mark depletion to roll with Cunning instead of Finesse.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Dismantle","trigger":"When you dismantle a broken or disabled piece of equipment or machinery, clear 2-depletion.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Cleave","Harry","Improvise","Trick Shot"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Counterfeit","Disable Device","Pick Lock"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 8"],"extras":{"startingValue":8}},{"name":"The Vagrant","blurb":"You are a charming, survivor vagabond, using words to get out of dangerous situations, perhaps even setting possible predators upon each other to keep them away from yourself.\n\nDeceitful, tricksy, charming, social. The Vagrant is a consummate con artist, a trickster and huckster who gets their way by sweet-talking and lying past trouble.\n\nThe Vagrant is a bit like the Adventurer meets the Thief—a charismatic talker who relies on deception for survival and for gain. They are likely to try to push to the front of the band whenever talking (and especially whenever lying) is involved. As the campaign progresses, however, they might find themself in a tight spot. Their lies generally won't lead to prestige gains with the deceived faction, so at some point, the Vagrant should probably pick one faction they're not going to con left and right…unless, of course, they're okay being on every faction's bad side.\n\nAs with all vagabonds, the Vagrant works best in the \"has a heart of gold\" mode. If the Vagrant has no shame about deceiving anyone and everyone, including innocents and victims of oppressors, then they're going to become unlikable fast. Testing the boundaries of how far the Vagrant will go to land their tricks is part of the character development of the playbook, and a Vagrant player should almost always have some limit to how far they will go.","stats":{"Charm":2,"Cunning":1,"Finesse":-1,"Luck":0,"Might":0},"natureChoose":1,"natures":[{"name":"Glutton","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you overindulge on vices like drink, food, and gambling."},{"name":"Hustler","condition":"Clear your exhaustion track when you try to spring a con on a powerful or dangerous mark."}],"driveChoose":2,"drives":[{"name":"Chaos","condition":"Advance when you topple a tyrannical or dangerously overbearing figure or order."},{"name":"Thrills","condition":"Advance when you escape from certain death or incarceration."},{"name":"Clean Paws","condition":"Advance when you accomplish an illicit, criminal goal while maintaining a believable veneer of innocence."},{"name":"Wanderlust","condition":"Advance when you finish a journey to a clearing."}],"connections":["Family: After ____________ and I pulled off an impressive heist and stole something very valuable from a powerful faction, my bad choices landed me in dire straits. But they bailed me out, and we've been close ever since.","Watcher: ____________ saw through one of my cons, and turned it back on me. How? Why did we forgive each other?"],"playbookMovesChoose":3,"playbookMoves":[{"name":"Instigator","trigger":"When you trick an NPC into fighting another NPC, you can remove one option from the 7-9 list—they cannot choose that option instead of doing what you want.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Pleasant Facade","trigger":"When you suck up to or otherwise butter up an unsuspecting NPC, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"10+":"hold 3. Spend your hold 1 for 1 to deflect their suspicion or aggression away from you onto someone or something else.","7-9":"hold 2. Spend your hold 1 for 1 to deflect their suspicion or aggression away from you onto someone or something else.","miss":"your attempts at flattery are suspicious—they're going to keep their eye on you."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Desperate Smile","trigger":"When you trust fate to see you through by begging, pleading, or abasing yourself, roll with Charm instead of Luck.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Charm Offensive","trigger":"When you play upon an enemy's insecurities, concerns, or fears to distract them with words during a fight, roll with Cunning.","outcomes":{"hit":"you create an opening for yourself—make any available weapon move against them at +1, or strike quickly and deal injury to them.","7-9":"you also tick them off; they aren't listening to you anymore, no matter what you do, until the situation drastically changes.","miss":"you infuriate them—they come at you, hard, and you're not prepared."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Let's Play","trigger":"When you play a game of skill and wit to loosen another's tongue, roll with Charm.","outcomes":{"hit":"they let slip something useful or valuable.","7-9":"you have to lose the game to get them there; mark depletion.","miss":"they're better than you ever thought; either mark depletion and cut your losses, or mark 3-depletion and they'll start talking."},"options":[],"notes":null},{"name":"Pocket Sand","trigger":"When you throw something to confuse an opponent's senses at close or intimate range, roll with Cunning instead of Finesse.","outcomes":null,"options":[],"notes":"Take the weapon skill Confuse Senses (it does not count against your limit)."}],"startingWeaponSkills":["Harry","Improvise","Quick Shot","Vicious Strike"],"startingRoguishFeats":["Pick Lock","Sleight of Hand"],"startingEquipment":["Starting Value 9"],"extras":{"startingValue":9}}],"notes":{"connectionTypes":"Connection prompts on each playbook use types such as Partner, Friend, Protector, Professional, Watcher, Family (full list on p.51 per advancement text).","weaponSkillsVsMoves":"A vagabond's weapon skill tags (from weapons/playbook) unlock the corresponding Weapon-category moves. Starting weapon skills are listed per playbook; max 7 total via advancement (not counting playbook-granted skills)."}};
